        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>1.</p>
    <p>Sci­en­tific re­search is like cook­ing</p>
    <p>First, plan a de­li­cious dish (an ex­per­i­ment that an­swers im­por­tant sci­en­tific ques­tions), and ap­ply hands-on skills in the kitchen (ex­e­cute the ex­per­i­ment suc­cess­fully in the lab­o­ra­tory).</p>
    <p>2. 3.</p>
    <p>Sci­ence is not like in the movies</p>
    <p>No fancy holo­graphic dis­plays, no in­stant analysis or cure when sam­ples are scanned. In­stead, it takes many years to even at­tempt to pro­duce some­thing that might be ap­plied in the real world.</p>
    <p>Sci­ence re­wards those who are pa­tient</p>
    <p>Most at­tempts ac­tu­ally fail. Hence, sci­en­tific re­search is for those who are adapt­able, imag­i­na­tive, but most of all, tena­cious.</p>


